OK, I can accept #33+#25 for FORCE and NORTH. In fact, for me this
will be the only use I make of #33, so it&#39;s easy to simply memorize
that this ligature is used for for &quot;or&quot; and &quot;oar&quot;.

Regarding Choice 1 vs. Choice 2, I could be persuaded in either
direction. I guess the important question is this: is there any accent
for which one of these choices would seem extremely unnatural?

Ted


On Nov 9, 2007 11:53 AM, John Cowan &lt;cowan@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; Ted Larson Freeman scripsit:
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;  &gt; I vote for Choice 1. After all, I&#39;m interested in reform--even in
&gt;  &gt; reforming the reform alphabet! Even so, I&#39;m willing to submit to the
&gt;  &gt; will of the majority on this one.
&gt;
&gt;  I don&#39;t think this is a matter for ballots, any more than for bullets.
&gt;  Rather, it&#39;s a question of persuasion. As I keep saying, there is a
&gt;  degree of arbitrariness in the choice, not least because many people
&gt;  don&#39;t clearly use either Eat or It in the NEAR set, but a vowel somewhere
&gt;  between.
&gt;
&gt;  The argument for Choice 1 (It, Et, Foot) is that more individuals speak
&gt;  that way. The argument for Choice 2 (Eat, Ate, Ooze) is that more accents
&gt;  use it and it is the historical one: it&#39;s no accident that Orthodox writes
&gt;  &quot;rear&quot; not &quot;rirr&quot; and &quot;square&quot; not &quot;squerr&quot;.
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;  &gt; Now let&#39;s turn to NORTH and FORCE. According to the handout you cited,
&gt;  &gt; &quot;In both standard accents, the FORCE words, historically distinct from
&gt;  &gt; NORTH words, have now become or are now in the process of becoming
&gt;  &gt; merged with them.&quot;
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; For the majority then, this would become an &#39;i before e&#39; type of rule:
&gt;  &gt; For &#39;long O&#39;, use &#39;Owe&#39; except before &#39;Roe&#39;, in which case use &#39;Awe&#39;.
&gt;  &gt; This feels unnatural to me.
&gt;
&gt;  I think you have it backwards. The NORTH words have always been
&gt;  pronounced as THOUGHT + /r/, except in accents where there is no separate
&gt;  THOUGHT vowel (that is, THOUGHT = PALM). &quot;Long O&quot; is GOAT, and it&#39;s the
&gt;  FORCE words that are GOAT + /r/ among people who make this distinction.
&gt;
&gt;  So what&#39;s happened is that the sound used in unmerged accents for FORCE
&gt;  has changed to the one used in all accents for NORTH. That&#39;s why it
&gt;  makes sense to use the NORTH spelling (Awe+Roe) for merged accents.
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;  &gt; On the other hand, what would be the cost of having the majority use
&gt;  &gt; &#39;Owe&#39; + &#39;Roe&#39; for both NORTH and FORCE?
&gt;
&gt;  The fact that for rhotic speakers that don&#39;t have THOUGHT = PALM,
&gt;  NORTH, FORCE, and THOUGHT have the same vowel (neglecting the /r/ for
&gt;  the moment), and that vowel is written Awe.
&gt;
&gt;  My dialect is one of these, and for me &quot;foh+rce&quot; and &quot;noh+rth&quot; are
&gt;  extremely unnatural renderings of these words.
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;  &gt; Couldn&#39;t those who distinguish the two still do so by using &#39;Owe&#39;
&gt;  &gt; and &#39;Awe&#39; as appropriate?
&gt;
&gt;  Absolutely.
